metadata.name: Emergence #9
metadata.description: This project was supposed to be released in a global one containing also my previous one Rupture. However, even if they were close in the intent by achieving some interesting pattern through a very sensitive balance between numerous parameters, they have resulted in output that can clearly appeal to different sensitivities. Then, I have prefered to separate them (and it was a bit easier to deal with the code ^^).

metadata.name: hollow #57
metadata.description:
In 1993, Basque sculptor Eduardo Chillida proposed a project to create an immense void inside Tindaya, the Sacred Mountain of Fuerteventura's indigenous inhabitants. The hollow cube measuring approximately 45 x 50 x 65 meters was conceived as a space for "all the people" to "fully experience the tininess of humankind".

The idea of the project dates back to the 1980s, and it took the artist years of searching for the ideal mountain in different parts of the world. However, what was ideal for Chillida evoked a lot of controversy due to the environmental and social impact of the project. There was uncertainty about Tindaya's structural feasibility and the potential harm to the ancient petroglyphs engraved on its surface. What's more, the financial sustainability of the project's economic model would depend on hundreds of thousands of tourists visiting the site each year, converting a work of art into a holiday attraction.

Chillida called his project the Monument to Tolerance. Although it never came into existence, it has caused division and conflict since it was conceived.


"hollow" is an exploration of 256 voids in nonexistent natural monuments. Made of digital matter instead of stone and lacking cultural charge, its sole purpose is to contemplate the tininess of humankind.


-----

Click on the image to open the menu. You may choose the quality from preview to the resolution of a print of approximately 30cm in height. In live mode, click on PNG to save the rendered image.

Depending on the device and CPU usage, it takes from a few seconds (on fast computers) to a minute (sometimes more) on mid-tier phones to render the image. 

Requirements: 1GB of RAM. The system needs up to 200 MB of free RAM for rendering square preview images and up to 400 MB of free RAM for rendering square images at the highest resolution. I tested on Chrome, Safari, Firefox, Edge / Windows, Mac OS, Android, and iPhone, but please make sure it works on your device before minting.

-----

Possible features:

color scheme: cairngorm, alborz, bardenas, atlas, bieszczady, watkins

proportions: square, wide, standard, narrow

frame: none, vignette, bright, dark, bright with vignette, dark with vignette

visitors: tourists, tourists and birds, solitary flock of birds, only light

metadata.name: Divers N1 #7
metadata.description:
I remember holding my breath and sitting on the bottom of the public pool where I spent most summers. Every so often I would hear a sound like breaking glass played by a transistor radio  and turn see the form of a diver plunging into the deep end. 

Consider the form of a diver seconds after they hit water. I am struck the grace of a freefall, the shock of transition from air to water, and the shedding of bits the old world carried with the skin. 

Formally this piece is also my attempt to blend a kind of lyrical figurativism with the technical and aesthetic demands of long-form token based generative art. In this piece, a randomized subset of digitally sculpted  forms are loaded, spatially transformed via heuristics and RNG, and then translated into simple animated particle systems. 

This process of transformation occurs a variable number of times, so each piece could contain the base form of anywhere between 1 and 10 divers.

this piece was created with threejs

metadata.name: fxEinstein #36
metadata.description:
I have traditionally paid special attention to studying the biographies of great personalities. The more I was immersed in their lives, imagining myself in their shoes, the more often I met their eyes in my reflection.

I began to wonder, "What if?" What if one of my idols had been born in France or England, for example. Or maybe in Ukraine, or Italy... Most likely, it would have been a completely different person. Perhaps Albert Einstein from Italy would never have been able to change the modern understanding of Physics, but surely the hooligan glasses could have added color to his Italian personality. Or perhaps the smoking pipe? Suddenly the English Albert would become the detective who would later become the hero of Conan Doyle's novel... 

Then or now? Maybe he would have liked to walk around at home in a vest, and his fascination with music and rock concerts, where he and his friends threw a "horns" to a band performing, revealed Albert to the masses in a very different way.

Albert Einstein is a great man. His ideas and thoughts still haunt the public mind to this day. Excerpts from the ideas of one of the founders of theoretical physics do not lose their relevance even today. They could come from any image of Einstein.

KRCHR Â©

Self-taught artist. I love physics and mathematics. I love the world around me. I love studying it. To be honest, this work is special to me. As I said above, Albert Einstein is my idol.
